22:59.044 --> 23:00.813 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
DAVID REITZE, California
Institute of Technology:
Actually, you did a pretty good
job.

23:00.913 --> 23:06.986 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, gravitational waves are
fluctuations in
space-time. And any time you
have a mass,

23:07.086 --> 23:13.058 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
something that has matter in it,
accelerating,
all right, it produces a
gravitational wave.

23:13.158 --> 23:17.596 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
All right? And that's a
consequence of Einstein's
theory of general relativity.

23:17.696 --> 23:22.401 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Now, these particular
gravitational waves,
in order to be able to detect
them, you need

23:22.501 --> 23:26.405 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
