them.

23:29.742 --> 23:33.646 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, why gravitational waves are
so interesting
is that they tell us something
about the universe

23:33.746 --> 23:39.051 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that you can't get from any
other kind of
astronomy. So, if you think
about optical

23:39.151 --> 23:43.889 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
astronomy, that looks at certain
classes of
light. If you look at radio
astronomy -- so

23:43.989 --> 23:46.392 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
gravitational waves are
completely different.

23:46.492 --> 23:51.730 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They come from a different
sector of the universe,
and that's why they're so
exciting.

23:51.830 --> 23:55.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: OK. So
Einstein is sitting
at his patent clerk's office
thinking about

23:55.100 --> 23:57.202 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
