and space
bent just a little bit at those
points?

24:07.579 --> 24:11.984 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVE REITZE: Oh, in fact, this
particular
event was, as my colleague Kip
Thorne calls

24:12.084 --> 24:14.019 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
it, a storm in space-time.

24:14.119 --> 24:18.657 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
All right? As these two black
holes came together
and collided, they really
disrupted space-time

24:18.757 --> 24:24.330 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and produced this burst of
gravitational radiation.
It's interesting that you
mention Einstein.

24:24.430 --> 24:29.301 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Gravitational waves were first
predicted actually
100 years ago. And Einstein
himself, all right,

24:29.401 --> 24:32.905 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
thought it was an interesting
consequence
of the theory of relativity, but
didn't think

24:33.005 --> 24:36.975 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that it had any practical value,
because he
said that the effect is so tiny
that we will

24:37.076 --> 24:38.877 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
never be able to measure them.

24:38.977 --> 24:43.716 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it took 100 years from the
time that he
predicted them to the time we
have been able

24:43.816 --> 24:45.651 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to measure them.

24:45.751 --> 24:47.386 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And, also, to
measure them,
you have very giant antennae
that most people

24:47.486 --> 24:50.622 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
